'''''Rainbow Warrior''''' is a video game for home computers produced by [[Greenpeace]], developed in association with Source the Software House and published by [[MicroStyle]] in 1989. Versions were released for the [[Commodore 64]],<ref>{{Citation|last=Tony Gibson|title=Dolphins - green@ngelband C64|date=2009-10-28|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=dL83QpSx1uU|access-date=2018-01-13}}</ref> [[Amiga]]<ref>{{Citation|last=FunCade 64|title=Rainbow Warrior ~ Amiga|date=2017-04-21|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=X7QtHYqbT4g|access-date=2018-01-13}}</ref> and [[Atari ST]].<ref>{{Citation|last=Stefan Lindberg|title=Rainbow Warrior - [Atari ST] Gameplay (1989)|date=2014-05-10|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lfeyoN3sSq8|access-date=2018-01-13}}</ref> The game is a collection of mini-games which relate to Greenpeace's environmental campaigns and actions during the 1980s.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mobygames.com/game/rainbow-warrior|title=Rainbow Warrior for Amiga (1989) - MobyGames|website=MobyGames|access-date=2018-01-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UOPgAwAAQBAJ&q=%22rainbow+warrior%22+computer+game&pg=PT124|title=The Green Case (Routledge Revivals): A Sociology of Environmental Issues, Arguments and Politics|last=Yearley|first=Steven|date=2014-06-23|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9781317702993|language=en}}</ref> A printed booklet containing further information about the environmental campaigns accompanied the game. It was manufactured in the United Kingdom and claimed to be "the first environment friendly software". The game was officially launched aboard the [[Rainbow Warrior II]] with Doug Faulkner and Jonathan Smales representing Greenpeace.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Webb|first=Trenton|date=1989-11-01|title=Rainbow Warrior|url=http://www.atarimania.com/game-atari-st-rainbow-warrior_10355.html|journal=ST Format|pages=78}}</ref>

== Development ==
The game was designed by Tony Gibson and Mark Harrison based on an original concept by Stevie Harrison. The music was composed by Paul Summers. The Atari ST version was programmed by Dave Semmens, Adrian Scothey and Ian Richards, with graphics by John Cassells, Tony Fawcett, Mark Scott and Bryn Redman.<ref name="petsasjim1 2013">{{Citation|last=petsasjim1|title=ATARI ST RAINBOW WARRIORS AKA RAINBOW WARRIOR|date=2013-07-21|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YXbv5Ldrnfc|access-date=2018-01-13}}</ref>

